an (or an ironic nickname for a big man), or a distinguishing name for the younger of two bearers of the same personal name. Compare   Little  ,   Petee  , and   Petite  .","History: Charles Petit from Anneville-Ambourville in Seine-Maritime, France, married Jeanne Rossignol (Martin and Renée Desjardins) in Quebec City, QC, in 1670. Nicolas Petit <i>dit</i> Lapré/Laprée from Le Gué-d'Alleré in Charente-Maritime, France, married Marie Pouponnel in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1656. Pierre Petit <i>dit</i> Gobin from Lyon in Rhône married Marguerite Véron in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1692. Pierre Petit <i>dit</i> Saint-Pierre from Évreux in Eure, France, married Judith Miville in Quebec City, QC, in 1758; see also   St. Pierre  . — This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."],"variants":[{"name":"Pattee","meanings":["Altered form of French (Nord) <b>Pety</b>: variant of   Petit  . This surname was brought to North America from England."]},{"name":"Petion","meanings":["French and Haitian (<b>Pétion</b>): diminutive of   Petit  . This surname was brought to the US from Haiti, where it is by far most common."]},{"name":"Petite","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Celestine, Jacques.","French: from the feminine form of   Petit   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"Petitt","meanings":["English: variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Pettett","meanings":["English: variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Little","meanings":["English: nickname for a small man (if not ironic), or distinguishing epithet for the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, from Middle English <i>littel</i>, Old English <i>lȳtel</i> (see   Light   3).","Irish: translation into English of Gaelic <b>Ó Beagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Beagán</i>’ (see   Began  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of any of various European surnames meaning ‘little’, e.g. French   Petit  , Polish <b>Mały</b> (see   Maly   1)."]},{"name":"Petee","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Pettie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Pettit","meanings":["English (mainly southeastern): variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Petito","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Carmine, Pasquale, Antonio, Rocco, Alfonzo, Alphonso, Antimo, Emilio, Giovanni, Giuseppe, Orazio, Salvatore, Silvio, Tullio, Virginio.","Italian: nickname for a small man (or an ironic nickname for a tall one), from dialect <i>petito</i> ‘small’ or from the personal name <i>Petito</i>; compare French   Petit  ."]}]},{"name":"Michaell","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of   Michael ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mikayla","meanings":["Modern respelling of   Michaela ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":36,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Michaell Petit was born about 1419, in Philleigh, Cornwall, England, his father, Michael Petit II, was 52 and his mother, Mrs. Michael Petit II, was 47. He married Julyan Talbot about 1412, in Philleigh, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"about 1419–":"umbes 1419–Surnud","1419–Male":"1419–Surnud","1390–Female":"1390–Surnud","1413–Male":"1413–Surnud","1437–1532":"1437–1532","1369–1455":"1369–1455","1373–Female":"1